sorcer.core.provider

Class ServiceProvider

  • java.lang.Object
    • sorcer.core.provider.ServiceProvider
  • All Implemented Interfaces:

    public class ServiceProvider
extends java.lang.Object
implements Identifiable, Provider, net.jini.lookup.ServiceIDListener, net.jini.id.ReferentUuid, net.jini.export.ProxyAccessor, net.jini.security.proxytrust.ServerProxyTrust, net.jini.core.constraint.RemoteMethodControl, org.rioproject.admin.ServiceActivityProvider, com.sun.jini.start.LifeCycle, Partner, Partnership, SorcerConstants, AdministratableProvider, ScratchManager
    The ServiceProvider class is a type of Provider with dependency injection defined by a Jini 2 configuration, proxy management, and own service discovery management for registering its proxies. This class can be inherited by custom service providers or used as a container for service beans - objects that implement Java interfaces to be exposed as service types. Service beans are declared in a provider configuration file as an array of dataBeans. A bean can be declared with a static method, e.g., MyServiceBean.buildMyBean($data), where $data refers to provider properties passed as argument of the static method buildMyBean of the class MyServiceBean.

    In the simplest case, the provider exports and registers its own (outer) proxy with the primary methods Service.exec(Arg[]) and service federation request Exerter.exert(Mogram, Transaction, Arg[]). The functionality of an outer proxy can be extended by its inner server functionality with its Remote inner proxy. In this case, the outer proxies have to implement Outer interface and each outer proxy is registered with the inner proxy allocated with Outer.getInner() invoked on the outer proxy. Obviously an outer proxy can implement own interfaces with the help of its embedded inner proxy that in turn can consist of multiple own inner proxies as needed. This class implements the Outer interface, so can extend its functionality by inner proxying.

    A smart proxy can be defined in the provider's Jini configuration by the smartProxy entry. This proxy does not represent directly any exported server, it is registered with lookup services as is. However, the smart proxy (implementing Outer interface) can extend its functionality by setting the providers outer proxy as its inner proxy. Thus, smart proxies that implementOuter, called semismart contain this provider's proxy as its inner proxy. Smart proxies that do not extend its functionality via its inner proxy are called fat proxies. Fat proxies do not make remote calls back to their providers and the providers just maintain lookup service registrations.

    An inner or outer proxy can be a surrogate of a service partner defined by this provider using server configuration entry or two realted args: serverType and serverName. If the entry server is defined and its exporter is defined by the entry serverExporter then this provider will use the server's proxy as the outer (primary proxy) and itself as the inner proxy. However if the exporter is not defined then the provider's proxy is primary (outer) and the server's proxy is the inner one.

    On the other hand, if the server entry is not defined but at least serverType is defined then the instance of server is created and exported if the entry serverExporter is given. The exported server proxy becomes the primary provider's proxy. However, if no exporter is defined then server proxy becomes the inner proxy of this provider's proxy (outer proxy). Thus, exported servers use outer proxies while not exported user inner proxies of this provider. In this context, a smart proxy implementing Outer interface can get the outer proxy and its inner proxy composed in either direction provider/server proxy relationship.

    A service method is a method returning ServiceContext and having a single parameter as ServiceContext. Service beans are components that implement interfaces in terms of service methods only. A list of service beans can be specified in a provider's Jini configuration as the beans entry. In this case a proxy implementing all interfaces implemented by service beans are dynamically created and registered with lookup services. Multiple SORCER servers can be deployed within a single ServiceProvider as its own service beans.
